title: For Sale/Trade:  Spanish FR8 Mauser Carbine Scout Rifle
postcontent:
Up for trade/sale is a nice Spanish FR8 Mauser Carbine Scout Rifle.
This FR-8 was developed from the Model 1943 short rifle, which was based on "large ring" K98 Model 1898 Mauser action.
This specimen was adopted into the Spanish Military in 1956 as the La Coruna.
The rifle was modified to fire the 7.62×51mm CETME and 7.62×51mm NATO rounds and was used well into the 1970s by mounted Guardia Civil units in the Sierra Nevada.
The FR-8 is an example of the type of carbine recommended by Jeff Cooper as a Scout rifle in the early 1970s, and bears a strong resemblance to the Ruger Gunsite Scout Rifle introduced in 2010.
The flash hider was designed to be compatible with NATO-standard rifle grenades.
The under-barrel tube, which resembles the gas cylinder found on automatic weapons, actually serves as the bayonet mount and as storage for cleaning gear.
The rear sight is an elevation-adjustable rotary type with aperatures for 200 m (220 yd), 300 m (330 yd) and 400 m (440 yd), as well as an open "V" notch for 100 metres (110 yd).
The front sight is elevation-adjustable via a special tool and Operation is identical to the standard Mauser design.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Sale Pending: Colt 1927 Sistema/1911 Argentine
postcontent: I have for sale or trade a beautiful Colt 1927 Sistema. The 1927 Sistemas are the same gun as a regular 1911A1 but were manufactured for and issued to the Argentine military and police forces. They are considered authentic mil spec 1911s by Colt and Colt collectors. In 1927, the Argentine Arsenal began manufacturing the Model 1911A1, production continued through 1966. The slide on this firearm is marked on each side with lines that read "EJERCITO ARGENTINO SIST.COLT.CAL. 11.25mm MOD.1927" which means Argentine Army, Sistema Colt, and notes the caliber, and the model number. The other side is stamped "DGFM FMAP" which stands for  (D.G.F.M.)  Direccion General de Fabricaciones Militares or the "Military Manufacturing Agency." (F.M.A.P.) Fabrica Militar de Armas Portatiles or "Small Arms Factory. These guns were made in Argentina under license from Colt, with Colt machinery, and with the help & supervision of Colt engineers. They are known as "Model 1927 Sistema Colt" or Colt system. Parts from the 1927 Sistema are interchangable with those of the 1911A1 unlike the later Ballester Molina models. According to the serial number, mine was one of six hundred manufactured in 1963. This .45 looks, feels and shoots beautifully, all serial numbers match and the pakrerizing is excellent. The gun has Pachmayr custom grips, comes with seven magazines, the original grips and a Blackhawk Serpa OWB right hand holster. Cash price is $900.00 but I'm also looking for a lever action deer gun and I'm willing to do some trading. You can own a piece of military history. This gun would look beautiful displayed or can still be carried everyday. I have a CCW and I would prefer you have one as well or at least have an Ohio Drivers License and be willing to sign a bill of sale. If this ad is still up, the gun is still available. Thank you for looking. Have a good day.
